   <mods:abstract>Was appointed a superintendent of highways by John Jay when governor. When
            superceded by Mr. Edwards, also a superintendent but who, up to that time, had not
            attended to any of the business, he was afraid it might have been due to a prejudicial
            report by a Mr. Mathews, nephew of the mayor of New York at that time. Hopes Jay will
            believe him a sincere friend. His acceptance of the presidency of the Bible Society
            gives pleasure, even though his bishop is said to "smell too strong of Calvinism."
            Thinks and hopes that we cannot be saved by our works, but only by grace or favor of
            God.</mods:abstract>
